# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: india
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:india/0-number] As a numerical digit, 0 plays a crucial role in decimal notation: it indicates that the power of ten corresponding to the place containing a 0 does not contribute to the total.
[src:india/0-number] For example, "205" in decimal means two hundreds, no tens, and five ones.
[src:india/0-number] The same principle applies in place-value notations that uses a base other than ten, such as binary and hexadecimal.
[src:india/0-number] The modern use of 0 in this manner derives from Indian mathematics that was transmitted to Europe via medieval Islamic mathematicians and popularized by Fibonacci.
[src:india/0-number] Common names for the number 0 in English include *zero*, *nought*, *naught* (/nɔːt/), and *nil*.
[src:india/0-number] In contexts where at least one adjacent digit distinguishes it from the letter O, the number is sometimes pronounced as *oh* or *o* (/oʊ/).
[src:india/0-number] Informal or slang terms for 0 include *zilch* and *zip*.
[src:india/0-number] Historically, *ought*, *aught* (/ɔːt/), and *cipher* have also been used.
[src:india/0-number] The word *zero* came into the English language via French *zéro* from the Italian *zero*, a contraction of the Venetian *zevero* form of Italian *zefiro*, itself borrowed from Arabic *ṣafira* or *ṣifr*.
[src:india/0-number] In pre-Islamic time the word *ṣifr* (Arabic صفر) had the meaning "empty".
[src:india/0-number] *Sifr* evolved to mean zero when it was used to translate *śūnya* (Sanskrit: शून्य) from India.
[src:india/0-number] The earliest known use of *zero* as a loanword in English literature was 1598.
[src:india/0-number] 1250), who grew up in North Africa and is credited with introducing the decimal system to Europe, used the term *zephyrum*.
[src:india/0-number] This became *zefiro* in Italian, and was then contracted to *zero* via the Venetian form *zevero*.
[src:india/0-number] The Italian word *zefiro* was already in existence (meaning "west wind" from Latin and Greek *Zephyrus*) and may have influenced the spelling when transcribing Arabic *ṣifr*.
[src:india/0-number] Depending on the context, there may be different words used for the number zero, or the concept of zero.
[src:india/0-number] For the simple notion of lacking, the words "nothing" (although this is not accurate) and "none" are often used.
[src:india/0-number] The English words "nought" or "naught", "nil", and null are also synonymous.
[src:india/0-number] It is often called "oh" in the context of reading out a string of digits, such as telephone numbers, street addresses, credit card numbers, military time, or years.
[src:india/0-number] For example, the area code 201 may be pronounced "two oh one", and the year 1907 is often pronounced "nineteen oh seven".
[src:india/0-number] The presence of other digits, indicating that the string contains only numbers, avoids confusion with the letter O.
[src:india/0-number] For this reason, systems that include strings with both letters and numbers (such as postcodes in the UK) may exclude the use of the letter O.
[src:india/0-number] Slang words for zero include "zip", "zilch", "nada", and "scratch".
[src:india/0-number] In the context of sports, "nil" is sometimes used, especially in British English.
[src:india/0-number] Several sports have specific words for a score of zero, such as "love" in tennis – possibly from French *l'œuf*, "the egg" – and "duck" in cricket, a shortening of "duck's egg".
[src:india/0-number] "Goose egg" is another general slang term used for zero.
[src:india/0-number] The concept of zero plays multiple roles in mathematics: as a digit, it is an important part of positional notation for representing numbers, while it also plays an important role as a number in its own right in many algebraic settings.
[src:india/0-number] In positional number systems (such as the usual decimal notation for representing numbers), the digit 0 plays the role of a placeholder, indicating that certain powers of the base do not contribute.
[src:india/0-number] For example, the decimal number 205 is the sum of two hundreds and five ones, with the 0 digit indicating that no tens are added.
[src:india/0-number] The digit plays the same role in decimal fractions and in the decimal representation of other real numbers (indicating whether any tenths, hundredths, thousandths, etc., are present) and in bases other than 10 (for example, in binary, where it indicates which powers of 2 are omitted).
[src:india/0-number] The number 0 is the smallest nonnegative integer, and the largest nonpositive integer.
[src:india/0-number] The natural number following 0 is 1 and no natural number precedes 0.
[src:india/0-number] The number 0 may or may not be considered a natural number, but it is an integer, and hence a rational number and a real number.
[src:india/0-number] Zero is even (that is, a multiple of 2), and is also an integer multiple of any other integer.
[src:india/0-number] It is neither a prime number nor a composite number.
[src:india/0-number] The number 0 is regarded as neither positive nor negative, and is usually displayed as the origin of a number line.
[src:india/0-number] When the real numbers are extended to form the complex numbers, 0 becomes the origin of the complex plane.
[src:india/0-number] The following are some basic rules for dealing with the number 0.
[src:india/0-number] These rules apply for any real or complex number *x*, unless otherwise stated.
[src:india/0-number] The expression ⁠0/0⁠, which may be obtained in an attempt to determine the limit of an expression of the form ⁠*f*(*x*)/*g*(*x*)⁠ as a result of applying the lim operator independently to both operands of the fraction, is a so-called "indeterminate form".
[src:india/0-number] That does not mean that the limit sought is necessarily undefined; rather, it means that the limit of ⁠*f*(*x*)/*g*(*x*)⁠, if it exists, must be found by another method, such as l'Hôpital's rule.
[src:india/0-number] The sum of 0 numbers (the *empty sum*) is 0, and the product of 0 numbers (the *empty product*) is 1.
[src:india/0-number] The factorial 0! evaluates to 1, as a special case of the empty product.
[src:india/0-number] The role of 0 as the smallest counting number can be generalized or extended in various ways.
[src:india/0-number] In set theory, 0 is the cardinality of the empty set (notated as "{ }", " ${\textstyle \emptyset }$ ", or "∅"): if one does not have any apples, then one has 0 apples.
[src:india/0-number] In fact, in certain axiomatic developments of mathematics from set theory, 0 is *defined* to be the empty set.
[src:india/0-number] When this is done, the empty set is the von Neumann cardinal assignment for a set with no elements, which is the empty set.
[src:india/0-number] Also in set theory, 0 is the lowest ordinal number, corresponding to the empty set viewed as a well-ordered set.
[src:india/0-number] In order theory (and especially its subfield lattice theory), 0 may denote the least element of a lattice or other partially ordered set.
[src:india/0-number] The role of 0 as additive identity generalizes beyond elementary algebra.
[src:india/0-number] In abstract algebra, 0 is commonly used to denote a zero element, which is the identity element for addition (if defined on the structure under consideration) and an absorbing element for multiplication (if defined).
[src:india/0-number] Examples include identity elements of additive groups and vector spaces.
[src:india/0-number] Another example is the **zero function** (or **zero map**) on a domain D.
[src:india/0-number] This is the constant function with 0 as its only possible output value, that is, it is the function f defined by *f*(*x*) = 0 for all x in D.
[src:india/0-number] As a function from the real numbers to the real numbers, the zero function is the only function that is both even and odd.
[src:india/0-number] Ancient Egyptian numerals were of base 10.
[src:india/0-number] They used hieroglyphs for the digits and were not positional.
[src:india/0-number] In one papyrus written around 1770 BC, a scribe recorded daily incomes and expenditures for the pharaoh's court, using the *nfr* hieroglyph to indicate cases where the amount of a foodstuff received was exactly equal to the amount disbursed.
[src:india/0-number] Egyptologist Alan Gardiner suggested that the *nfr* hieroglyph was being used as a symbol for zero.
[src:india/0-number] The same symbol was also used to indicate the base level in drawings of tombs and pyramids, and distances were measured relative to the base line as being above or below this line.
[src:india/0-number] By the middle of the 2nd millennium BC, Babylonian mathematics had a sophisticated base 60 positional numeral system, but a positional value of zero was indicated by a *space* between numerals.
[src:india/0-number] In a tablet unearthed at Kish (dating to as early as 700 BC), the scribe Bêl-bân-aplu used three hooks as a placeholder.
[src:india/0-number] By 300 BC, a punctuation symbol (two slanted wedges) was repurposed as a placeholder.
[src:india/0-number] The Mesoamerican Long Count calendar developed in south-central Mexico and Central America required the use of zero as a placeholder within its vigesimal (base-20) positional numeral system.
[src:india/0-number] Many different glyphs, including the partial quatrefoil were used as a zero symbol for these Long Count dates, the earliest of which (on Stela 2 at Chiapa de Corzo, Chiapas) has a date of 36 BC.
[src:india/0-number] Since the eight earliest Long Count dates appear outside the Maya homeland, it is generally believed that the use of zero in the Americas predated the Maya and was possibly the invention of the Olmecs.
[src:india/0-number] Many of the earliest Long Count dates were found within the Olmec heartland, although the Olmec civilization ended by the 4th century BC, several centuries before the earliest known Long Count dates.
[src:india/0-number] Although zero became an integral part of Maya numerals, with a different, empty tortoise-like "shell shape" used for many depictions of the "zero" numeral, it is assumed not to have influenced Old World numeral systems.
[src:india/0-number] Quipu, a knotted cord device, used in the Inca Empire and its predecessor societies in the Andean region to record accounting and other digital data, is encoded in a base ten positional system.
[src:india/0-number] Zero is represented by the absence of a knot in the appropriate position.
[src:india/0-number] The earliest confidently cited exemplar of the Greek use of the Hellenistic zero appears in Hipparchus in 140 CE.
[src:india/0-number] The archaic Greece had no symbol for zero (μηδέν, pronounced *mēdén*), and did not use a digit placeholder for it.
[src:india/0-number] According to mathematician Charles Seife, after the Babylonian placeholder zero shows up sometime shortly after 500 BC, Greek astronomers began to use the lowercase Greek letter *ό* (*όμικρον*: omicron) as a placeholder or representation of ground-level/null degree value.
[src:india/0-number] However, after using the Babylonian placeholder zero for astronomical calculations they would typically convert the numbers back into Greek numerals.
[src:india/0-number] As with the rejection of infinitesimals by Pythagoras, Greeks appear to maintain to a philosophical opposition to using zero as a number.
[src:india/0-number] "The whole of the Greek universe rested on this pillar: There is no void." Nieder dates the appearance of zero in Greek astronomical texts after 400 BC and mathematician Robert Kaplan further specifies that it must have been after the conquests of Alexander.
[src:india/0-number] Greeks seemed unsure about the status of zero as a number.
[src:india/0-number] Some of them asked themselves, "How can not being be?", leading to philosophical and, by the medieval period, religious arguments about the nature and existence of zero and the vacuum.
[src:india/0-number] The paradoxes of Zeno of Elea depend in large part on the uncertain interpretation of zero.
[src:india/0-number] By AD 150, Ptolemy, influenced by Hipparchus and the Babylonians, was using a symbol for zero (—°) in his work on mathematical astronomy called the *Syntaxis Mathematica*, also known as the *Almagest*.
[src:india/0-number] This Hellenistic zero was perhaps the earliest documented use of a numeral representing zero in the Old World.
[src:india/0-number] Ptolemy used it many times in his *Almagest* (VI.8) for the magnitude of solar and lunar eclipses.
[src:india/0-number] It represented the value of both digits and minutes of immersion at first and last contact.
[src:india/0-number] Digits varied continuously from 0 to 12 to 0 as the Moon passed over the Sun (a triangular pulse), where twelve digits was the angular diameter of the Sun.
[src:india/0-number] Minutes of immersion was tabulated from 0′0″ to 31′20″ to 0′0″, where 0′0″ used the symbol as a placeholder in two positions of his sexagesimal positional numeral system, while the combination meant a zero angle.
[src:india/0-number] Minutes of immersion was also a continuous function ⁠1/12⁠ 31′20″ √d(24−d) (a triangular pulse with convex sides), where d was the digit function and 31′20″ was the sum of the radii of the Sun's and Moon's discs.
[src:india/0-number] Ptolemy's symbol was a placeholder as well as a number used by two continuous mathematical functions, one within another, so it meant zero, not none.
[src:india/0-number] Over time, Ptolemy's zero tended to increase in size and lose the overline, sometimes depicted as a large elongated 0-like omicron "Ο" or as omicron with overline "ō" instead of a dot with overline.
[src:india/0-number] This use was repeated in 525 in an equivalent table, that was translated via the Latin *nulla* ("none") by Dionysius Exiguus, alongside Roman numerals.
[src:india/0-number] When division produced zero as a remainder, *nihil*, meaning "nothing", was used.
[src:india/0-number] These medieval zeros were used by all future medieval calculators of Easter.
[src:india/0-number] The initial "N" was used as a zero symbol in a table of Roman numerals by Bede—or his colleagues—around AD 725.
[src:india/0-number] The *Sūnzĭ Suànjīng*, of unknown date but estimated to be dated from the 1st to 5th centuries AD, describe how the 4th century BC Chinese counting rods system enabled one to perform positional decimal calculations.
[src:india/0-number] As noted in the *Xiahou Yang Suanjing* (425–468 AD), to multiply or divide a number by 10, 100, 1000, or 10000, all one needs to do, with rods on the counting board, is to move them forwards, or back, by 1, 2, 3, or 4 places.
[src:india/0-number] The rods gave the decimal representation of a number, with an empty space denoting zero.
[src:india/0-number] A circa 190 AD, manual, the "Supplementary Notes on the Art of Figures", by Xu Yue, also outlines the techniques to add, subtract, multiply, and divide numbers, containing zero values in a decimal power, on *counting devices*, that include counting rods, and abacus.
[src:india/0-number] Chinese authors had been familiar with the idea of negative numbers, and decimal fractions, by the Han dynasty (2nd century AD), as seen in *The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art*.
[src:india/0-number] Qín Jiǔsháo's 1247 *Mathematical Treatise in Nine Sections* is the oldest surviving Chinese mathematical text using a round symbol '〇' for zero.
[src:india/0-number] The origin of this symbol is unknown; it may have been produced by modifying a square symbol.
[src:india/0-number] Zero was not treated as a number at that time, but as a "vacant position".
[src:india/0-number] A variety of Chinese characters have been used, through history, to represent zero: 空, 零, 洞, 〇.
[src:india/0-number] 3rd or 2nd century BC), a Sanskrit prosody scholar, used binary sequences, in the form of short and long syllables (the latter equal in length to two short syllables), to identify the possible valid Sanskrit meters, a notation similar to Morse code.
[src:india/0-number] Pingala used the Sanskrit word *śūnya* explicitly to refer to zero.
[src:india/0-number] A decimal place value grapheme for zero was developed in India.
[src:india/0-number] The *Lokavibhāga*, a Jain text on cosmology surviving in a medieval Sanskrit translation of the Prakrit original, which is internally dated to AD 458 (Saka era 380), uses a decimal place-value system, including a zero.
[src:india/0-number] In this text, *śūnya* ("void, empty") is also used to refer to zero.
[src:india/0-number] 499), states *sthānāt sthānaṁ daśaguṇaṁ syāt* "from place to place each is ten times the preceding".
[src:india/0-number] The oldest, firmly dated use of zero as a decimal figure, found on the Sambor Inscription.
[src:india/0-number] There are numerous copper plate inscriptions with the same small o in them, some of them possibly dated to the 6th century, but their date or authenticity may be open to doubt.
[src:india/0-number] A stone tablet found in the ruins of a temple near Sambor on the Mekong, Kratié Province, Cambodia, includes the inscription of "605" in Khmer numerals (a set of numeral glyphs for the Hindu–Arabic numeral system).
[src:india/0-number] The number is the year of the inscription in the Saka era, corresponding to a date of AD 683.
[src:india/0-number] The first known use of special glyphs for the decimal digits that includes the indubitable appearance of a symbol for the digit zero, a small circle, appears on a stone inscription found at the Chaturbhuj Temple, Gwalior, in India, dated AD 876.
[src:india/0-number] A symbol for zero, a black dot, is used throughout the Bakhshali manuscript, a practical manual on arithmetic for merchants.
[src:india/0-number] The Bodleian Library reported radiocarbon dating results for six folio from the manuscript, indicating that they came from different centuries, but date the manuscript to AD 799 – 1102.
[src:india/0-number] The Arabic-language inheritance of science was largely Greek, followed by Hindu influences.
[src:india/0-number] In 773, at Al-Mansur's behest, translations were made of many ancient treatises including Greek, Roman, Indian, and others.
[src:india/0-number] In AD 813, astronomical tables were prepared by a Persian mathematician, Muḥammad ibn Mūsā al-Khwārizmī, using Hindu numerals; and about 825, he published a book synthesizing Greek and Hindu knowledge and also contained his own contribution to mathematics including an explanation of the use of zero.
[src:india/0-number] This book was later translated into Latin in the 12th century under the title *Algoritmi de numero Indorum*.
[src:india/0-number] This title means "al-Khwarizmi on the Numerals of the Indians".
[src:india/0-number] The word "Algoritmi" was the translator's Latinization of Al-Khwarizmi's name, and the word "Algorithm" or "Algorism" started to acquire a meaning of any arithmetic based on decimals.
[src:india/0-number] Muhammad ibn Ahmad al-Khwarizmi, in 976, stated that if no number appears in the place of tens in a calculation, a little circle should be used "to keep the rows".
[src:india/0-number] The Hindu–Arabic numeral system (base 10) reached Western Europe in the 11th century, via Al-Andalus, through Spanish Muslims, the Moors, together with knowledge of classical astronomy and instruments like the astrolabe.
[src:india/0-number] Gerbert of Aurillac is credited with reintroducing the lost teachings into Catholic Europe.
[src:india/0-number] For this reason, the numerals came to be known in Europe as "Arabic numerals".
[src:india/0-number] From the 13th century, manuals on calculation (adding, multiplying, extracting roots, etc.) became common in Europe where they were called *algorismus* after the Persian mathematician al-Khwārizmī.
[src:india/0-number] One popular manual was written by Johannes de Sacrobosco in the early 1200s and was one of the earliest scientific books to be printed, in 1488.
[src:india/0-number] The practice of calculating on paper using Hindu–Arabic numerals only gradually displaced calculation by abacus and recording with Roman numerals.
[src:india/0-number] In the 16th century, Hindu–Arabic numerals became the predominant numerals used in Europe.
[src:india/0-number] Today, the numerical digit 0 is usually written as a circle or ellipse.
[src:india/0-number] Traditionally, many print typefaces made the capital letter O more rounded than the narrower, elliptical digit 0.
[src:india/0-number] Typewriters originally made no distinction in shape between O and 0; some models did not even have a separate key for the digit 0.
[src:india/0-number] The distinction came into prominence on modern character displays.
[src:india/0-number] A slashed zero ( $0\!\!\!{/}$ ) is often used to distinguish the number from the letter (mostly in computing, navigation and in the military, for example).
[src:india/0-number] The digit 0 with a dot in the center seems to have originated as an option on IBM 3270 displays and has continued with some modern computer typefaces such as Andalé Mono, and in some airline reservation systems.
[src:india/0-number] One variation uses a short vertical bar instead of the dot.
[src:india/0-number] Some fonts designed for use with computers made the "0" character more squared at the edges, like a rectangle, and the "O" character more rounded.
[src:india/0-number] A further distinction is made in falsification-hindering typeface as used on German car number plates by slitting open the digit 0 on the upper right side.
[src:india/0-number] In some systems either the letter O or the numeral 0, or both, are excluded from use, to avoid confusion.
[src:india/0-number] The value zero plays a special role for many physical quantities.
[src:india/0-number] For some quantities, the zero level is naturally distinguished from all other levels, whereas for others it is more or less arbitrarily chosen.
[src:india/0-number] For example, for an absolute temperature (typically measured in kelvins), zero is the lowest possible value.
[src:india/0-number] (Negative temperatures can be defined for some physical systems, but negative-temperature systems are not actually colder.) This is in contrast to temperatures on the Celsius scale, for example, where zero is arbitrarily defined to be at the freezing point of water.
[src:india/0-number] Measuring sound intensity in decibels or phons, the zero level is arbitrarily set at a reference value—for example, at a value for the threshold of hearing.
[src:india/0-number] Modern computers store information in binary, that is, using an "alphabet" that contains only two symbols, usually chosen to be "0" and "1".
[src:india/0-number] Binary coding is convenient for digital electronics, where "0" and "1" can stand for the absence or presence of electrical current in a wire.
[src:india/0-number] Computer programmers typically use high-level programming languages that are more intelligible to humans than the binary instructions that are directly executed by the central processing unit.
[src:india/0-number] 0 plays various important roles in high-level languages.
[src:india/0-number] The most common practice throughout human history has been to start counting at one, and this is the practice in early classic programming languages such as Fortran and COBOL.
[src:india/0-number] For example, the elements of an array are numbered starting from 0 in C, so that for an array of *n* items the sequence of array indices runs from 0 to *n*−1.
[src:india/0-number] Since C arrays are accessed by the array's first element memory address plus an offset, the initial pointer plus with offset zero refers to the first element of the array.
[src:india/0-number] There can be confusion between 0- and 1-based indexing; for example, Java's JDBC indexes parameters from 1 although Java itself uses 0-based indexing.
[src:india/0-number] In C, a byte containing the value 0 serves to indicate where a string of characters ends.
[src:india/0-number] Also, 0 is a standard way to refer to a null pointer in code.
[src:india/0-number] In databases, it is possible for a field not to have a value.
[src:india/0-number] For numeric fields it is not the value zero.
[src:india/0-number] For text fields this is not blank nor the empty string.
[src:india/0-number] The presence of null values leads to three-valued logic.
[src:india/0-number] No longer is a condition either *true* or *false*, but it can be *undetermined*.
[src:india/0-number] Any computation including a null value delivers a null result.
[src:india/0-number] In mathematics, there is no "positive zero" or "negative zero" distinct from zero; both −0 and +0 represent exactly the same number.
[src:india/0-number] However, in some computer hardware signed number representations, zero has two distinct representations, a positive one grouped with the positive numbers and a negative one grouped with the negatives.
[src:india/0-number] This kind of dual representation is known as signed zero, with the latter form sometimes called negative zero.
[src:india/0-number] These representations include the signed magnitude and ones' complement binary integer representations (but not the two's complement binary form used in most modern computers), and most floating-point number representations (such as IEEE 754 and IBM S/360 floating-point formats).
[src:india/0-number] An epoch, in computing terminology, is the date and time associated with a zero timestamp.
[src:india/0-number] The Unix epoch begins the midnight before the first of January 1970.
[src:india/0-number] The Classic Mac OS epoch and Palm OS epoch begin the midnight before the first of January 1904.
[src:india/0-number] Many APIs and operating systems that require applications to return an integer value as an exit status typically use zero to indicate success and non-zero values to indicate specific error or warning conditions.
[src:india/0-number] Programmers often use a slashed zero to avoid confusion with the letter "O".
[src:india/0-number] In comparative zoology and cognitive science, recognition that some animals display awareness of the concept of zero leads to the conclusion that the capability for numerical abstraction arose early in the evolution of species.
[src:india/0-number] In the BC calendar era, the year 1 BC is the first year before AD 1; there is not a year zero.
[src:india/0-number] By contrast, in astronomical year numbering, the year 1 BC is numbered 0, the year 2 BC is numbered −1, and so forth.
[src:india/10th-brics-summit] The **2018 BRICS summit** is the tenth annual BRICS summit, an international relations conference attended by the heads of state or heads of government of the five member states of BRICS at the time: Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa.
[src:india/10th-brics-summit] The summit was held in Johannesburg, South Africa, the second time that South Africa has hosted the summit with the first being the 2013 summit.
[src:india/10th-brics-summit] Convened with the theme of "*BRICS in Africa: Collaboration for Inclusive Growth and Shared Prosperity in the 4th Industrial Revolution*", the next BRICS Summit set to take place in Brazil, have enjoyed the full support of the other member states along with its Chairship in 2019.
[src:india/11th-brics-summit] The **2019 BRICS summit** was the eleventh annual BRICS summit, an international relations conference to be attended by the heads of state or heads of government of the five member states Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa.
[src:india/11th-brics-summit] The meeting was held at the Itamaraty Palace, where the Brazilian Ministry of Foreign Affairs is located.
[src:india/11th-brics-summit] The Brazilian capital hosted the BRICS summit for the second time.
[src:india/11th-brics-summit] The Sherpa meeting was held in the Brazilian city of Curitiba between March 14 and 15.
[src:india/11th-brics-summit] The name of the chosen theme was: *BRICS: economic growth for an innovative future*.
[src:india/12th-brics-summit] The **2020 BRICS summit** was the twelfth annual BRICS summit, an international relations conference attended by the heads of state or heads of government of the five member states Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa.
[src:india/12th-brics-summit] The meeting was originally scheduled to take place in Saint Petersburg from July 21 to 23, 2020, but was changed to a video conference held on November 17 due to the outbreak of the global COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:india/12th-brics-summit] Russia last chaired 7th BRICS summit, Ufa.
[src:india/12th-brics-summit] The 1st Sherpa meeting was held in Saint Petersburg between 11 and 13 February 2020, under chairmanship of Sergei Ryabkov, Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and Russian Sherpa for BRICS.
[src:india/13th-brics-summit] The **2021 BRICS summit** is the thirteenth annual BRICS summit, an international relations conference attended by the heads of state or heads of government of the five member states Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa.
[src:india/13th-brics-summit] It was the third time that India hosted the BRICS Summit after 2012 and 2016.
[src:india/13th-brics-summit] The summit was hosted virtually by video conference.
[src:india/13th-brics-summit] The summit was taken virtually from New Delhi, India.
[src:india/13th-brics-summit] India hosted the first meeting of BRICS finance and central bank deputies through video conference.
[src:india/13th-brics-summit] The meeting was co-chaired by Michael Patra, Deputy Governor, Reserve Bank of India and Tarun Bajaj, Secretary Department of Revenue, Ministry of Finance, India.
[src:india/14th-brics-summit] The **2022 BRICS summit** is the fourteenth annual BRICS summit, an international relations conference attended by the heads of state or heads of government of the five member states Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa.
[src:india/14th-brics-summit] It was the third time that China hosted the BRICS Summit after 2011 and 2017.
[src:india/14th-brics-summit] A major development on the summit was creation of a new, basket type reserve currency.
[src:india/14th-brics-summit] The currency, combines BRICS currencies and is backed by precious metals.
[src:india/in] The domain was originally managed by the National Centre for Software Technology (NCST), Mumbai and its Centre for Development of Advanced Computing (C-DAC).
[src:india/in] The Government of India issued an executive order in 2004 to transfer responsibility for managing .in domains to the newly created INRegistry under the authority of the National Internet Exchange of India (NIXI).
[src:india/in] The National Informatics Centre (NIC), ERNET, and the Ministry of Defence were appointed as registrars for the gov.in, res.in and ac.in, and the mil.in domains respectively.
[src:india/in] From August 2012 to February 2019, the registry was managed under contract by Afilias India Pvt.
[src:india/in] In August 2018, NIXI appointed Neustar Data Infotech (India), a subsidiary of Neustar, Inc., to be the country's new registry services provider.
[src:india/in] Neustar completed migration of existing .in domains to its registry infrastructure in March 2019.
[src:india/in] Neustar added the ability to register Indian-language domains in native script by enabling end-to-end web portal language support.
[src:india/in] in February 2025, Tucows announced it won the contract to run the backend registry services for India’s .in country code domain.
[src:india/in] The company is migrating about 4 million .in domains to its platform.
[src:india/in] As of 2005, liberalised policies for the .in domain allow unlimited second-level registrations under .in.
[src:india/in] The domain .nic.in is reserved for India's National Informatics Centre, but in practice most Indian government agencies have domains ending in .nic.in.
[src:india/in] Before the introduction of liberalised registration policies for the .in domain, only 7000 names had been registered between 1992 and 2004.
[src:india/in] As of March 2010, the number had increased to over 610,000 domain names with 60% of registrations coming from India and the rest from overseas.
[src:india/in] By October 2011, the number had surpassed 1 million domain names.
[src:india/in] As of March 2016, the number has more than doubled to over 2 million domain names.
[src:india/in] As per the terms and conditions of the .in registry, domain privacy is not allowed.
[src:india/in] Recently updated EKYC guidelines were issued to all registrars to authenticate new registrants.
[src:india/in] Hence, the previous rule relating to bulk booking of .in domain names has been withdrawn.
[src:india/in] Now customers can book unlimited .in domain names as previously in line with promoting .in TLD on par with other popular TLDs like .com and others which also has no restrictions relating to bulk booking.
[src:india/in] India plans to introduce internationalised domain names in the 22 local languages used in the country.
[src:india/in] In 2016, an application for eight further domains was accepted.
[src:india/india-p01] Modern humans arrived on the Indian subcontinent from Africa no later than 55,000 years ago.
[src:india/india-p01] Their long occupation, predominantly in isolation as hunter-gatherers, has made the region highly diverse.
[src:india/india-p01] Settled life emerged on the subcontinent in the western margins of the Indus river basin 9,000 years ago, evolving gradually into the Indus Valley Civilisation of the third millennium BCE.
[src:india/india-p01] By 1200 BCE, an archaic form of Sanskrit, an Indo-European language, had diffused into India from the northwest.
[src:india/india-p01] Its hymns recorded the early dawnings of Hinduism in India.
[src:india/india-p01] India's pre-existing Dravidian languages were supplanted in the northern regions.
[src:india/india-p01] By 400 BCE, caste had emerged within Hinduism, and Buddhism and Jainism had arisen, proclaiming social orders unlinked to heredity.
[src:india/india-p01] Early political consolidations gave rise to the loose-knit Maurya and Gupta Empires.
[src:india/india-p01] During this era, there was a flourishing of creativity in art, architecture, and writing, the status of women declined, and untouchability became an organised belief.
[src:india/india-p01] In South India, the Middle kingdoms exported Dravidian language scripts and religious cultures to the kingdoms of Southeast Asia.
[src:india/india-p01] In the 1st millennium Islam, Christianity, Judaism, and Zoroastrianism became established on India's southern and western coasts.
[src:india/india-p01] Early in the 2nd millennium Muslim armies from Central Asia intermittently overran India's northern plains.
[src:india/india-p01] The resulting Delhi Sultanate drew northern India into the cosmopolitan networks of medieval Islam.
[src:india/india-p01] In south India, the Vijayanagara Empire created a long-lasting composite Hindu culture.
[src:india/india-p01] In the Punjab, Sikhism emerged, rejecting institutionalised religion.
[src:india/india-p01] The Mughal Empire ushered in two centuries of economic expansion and relative peace, and left a rich architectural legacy.
[src:india/india-p01] Gradually expanding rule of the British East India Company turned India into a colonial economy but consolidated its sovereignty.
[src:india/india-p01] The rights promised to Indians were granted slowly, but technological changes were introduced, and modern ideas of education and the public life took root.
[src:india/india-p01] A nationalist movement emerged in India, the first in the non-European British Empire and an influence on other nationalist movements.
[src:india/india-p01] Noted for nonviolent resistance after 1920, it became the primary factor in ending British rule.
[src:india/india-p01] In 1947, the British Indian Empire was partitioned into two independent dominions, a Hindu-majority dominion of India and a Muslim-majority dominion of Pakistan.
[src:india/india-p01] A large-scale loss of life and an unprecedented migration accompanied the partition.
[src:india/india-p01] India has been a federal republic since 1950, governed through a democratic parliamentary system.
[src:india/india-p01] It is a pluralistic, multilingual and multi-ethnic society.
[src:india/india-p01] India's population grew from 361 million in 1951 to over 1.4 billion in 2023.
[src:india/india-p01] During this time, its nominal per capita income increased from US$64 annually to US$2,601, and its literacy rate from 16.6% to 74%.
[src:india/india-p01] The Indian economy has since become a fast-growing major economy and a hub for information technology, with an expanding middle class.
[src:india/india-p01] India has reduced its poverty rate, though at the cost of increasing economic inequality.
[src:india/india-p01] It is a nuclear-weapon state that ranks high in military expenditure.
[src:india/india-p01] It has disputes over Kashmir with its neighbours, Pakistan and China, unresolved since the mid-20th century.
[src:india/india-p01] Among the socio-economic challenges India faces are gender inequality, child malnutrition, and rising levels of air pollution.
[src:india/india-p01] India's land is megadiverse with four biodiversity hotspots.
[src:india/india-p01] India's wildlife, which has traditionally been viewed with tolerance in its culture, is supported in protected habitats.
[src:india/india-p01] According to the *Oxford English Dictionary*, the English proper noun "India" derives most immediately from the Classical Latin *India*, a reference to a loosely-defined historical region of Asia stretching from South Asia to the borders of China.
[src:india/india-p01] Further etymons are: Hellenistic Greek *India* (Ἰνδία); Ancient Greek *Indos* (Ἰνδός), or the River Indus; Achaemenian Old Persian *Hindu* (an eastern province of the Achaemenid Empire); and Sanskrit *Sindhu*, or "river," but specifically the Indus river, and by extension its well-settled basin.
[src:india/india-p01] The Ancient Greeks referred to South Asians as *Indoi*, 'the people of the Indus'.
[src:india/india-p01] The term *Bharat* (*Bhārat*; pronounced [ˈbʱaːɾət] ⓘ), mentioned in both Indian epic poetry and the Constitution of India, is used in its variations by many Indian languages.
[src:india/india-p01] A modern rendering of the historical name *Bharatavarsha*, which applied originally to North India, *Bharat* gained increased currency from the mid-19th century as a native name for India.
[src:india/india-p01] Based on coalescence of Mitochondrial DNA and Y Chromosome data, it is thought that the earliest extant lineages of anatomically modern humans or *Homo sapiens* on the Indian subcontinent had reached there from Africa between 80,000 and 50,000 years ago, and with high likelihood by 55,000 years ago.
[src:india/india-p01] Their long occupation, initially in varying forms of isolation as hunter-gatherers, has made the region highly diverse, second only to Africa in human genetic diversity.
[src:india/india-p01] However, the earliest known modern human fossils in South Asia date to about 30,000 years ago.
[src:india/india-p01] Evidence for the neolithic period in the western margins of the Indus river basin, at Mehrgarh in Balochistan, Pakistan, dates to after 7000 BCE.
[src:india/india-p01] Domestication of grain-producing plants (including barley) and animals (including humped zebu cattle) occurred here.
[src:india/india-p01] These cultures gradually evolved into the Indus Valley Civilisation, which flourished during 2500–1900 BCE in Pakistan and western India.
[src:india/india-p01] Networks of towns and villages grew around the cities in a new agro-pastoral economy.
[src:india/india-p01] Between 1500 BCE and 1200 BCE, an archaic form of Sanskrit, an Indo-European language, diffused into India from the northwest.
[src:india/india-p01] Its evidence today is found in the Rig Veda—the oldest scripture associated with what later became Hinduism—which was composed by Indo-Aryan-speaking tribes migrating east from what is today northern Afghanistan and across the Punjab region.
[src:india/india-p01] The settling of the Ganges river plain took place during the next millennium, when large swathes of the river system's adjoining regions were deforested, at times by setting fires, or later by employing iron implements, and prepared for agriculture.
[src:india/india-p01] The settlement may have involved driving the preexisting people out or enslaving them.
[src:india/india-p01] The Dravidian languages of India were supplanted in the north, creating a broad language family-divide, with the Indo-Aryan languages being spoken mainly in the north and west, and the Dravidian in some parts of east India and most of the south.
[src:india/india-p01] Classical Sanskrit, a refined and standardised grammatical form would emerge in the mid-1st millennium BCE and was codified in the *Aṣṭādhyāyī* ('Eight chapters') of Pāṇini.
[src:india/india-p01] The two major Sanskrit epics, the Mahābhārata and the Rāmāyaṇa, however, were composed in a range of oral storytelling registers called Epic Sanskrit which was used in northern India between 400 BCE and 300 CE, and roughly contemporary with classical Sanskrit.
[src:india/india-p01] A second urbanisation had taken place in South Asia by 400 BCE, this time on the Ganges plain.
[src:india/india-p01] In fortified cities, social differentiation by caste, or varna, had emerged.
[src:india/india-p01] By the mid-millennium two new ethical and social systems had arisen: Jainism based on the teachings of Mahavira and Buddhism on those of the Buddha.
[src:india/india-p01] Both religions stressed non-violence and abjured animal sacrifices conducted in Brahmanism, and birth into a fixed hereditary *varna*.
[src:india/india-p01] By living ethically, lay people could rise socially and morally in these religions.
[src:india/india-p01] Chronicling the life of the Buddha was central to the beginnings of recorded history in India.
[src:india/india-p01] The rise of the two religions was a backdrop to the emergence of the first loose-knit geographically extensive power in South Asia, the Maurya Empire.
[src:india/india-p01] During the rule of the founder's grandson, Ashoka (ca.
[src:india/india-p01] 268–232 BCE), the empire briefly controlled the major urban hubs and arteries of the subcontinent, except in the deep south.
[src:india/india-p01] The empire's period was notable for creativity in art, architecture, inscriptions, and produced texts, but also for the declining rights of women in the mainstream Indo-Aryan speaking regions.
[src:india/india-p01] Following his conquest of Kalinga, in which his forces caused immense loss of life, Ashoka adopted Buddhism, subsequently adopting a policy of *dhamma* and commissioning numerous rock and pillar edicts throughout the Maurya Empire to promote ethical conduct, non-violence, and social welfare.
[src:india/india-p01] As the edicts forbade both the killing of wild animals and the destruction of forests, Ashoka is seen by some modern environmental historians as an early embodiment of that ethos.
[src:india/india-p01] By the 4th and 5th centuries, the Gupta Empire had created a complex system of administration and taxation in the greater Ganges Plain; this system became a model for later Indian kingdoms.
[src:india/india-p01] Under the Guptas, a renewed Hinduism based on devotion, rather than the management of ritual, began to assert itself.
[src:india/india-p01] The renewal was reflected in a flowering of art, literature, and science.
[src:india/india-p01] By the sixth century, the Pallavas had grown into a regional power.
[src:india/india-p01] Simultaneously, Buddhism and Jainism, which had favoured a conservative transactionalism, were replaced by kingly devotion to the gods of particular places, which became a characteristic of the Bhakti movement.
[src:india/india-p01] The Pallavas, in particular, traded extensively with the Roman Empire and with West and Southeast Asia.
[src:india/india-p01] The Indian early medieval age, from 600 to 1200 CE, was defined by regional kingdoms and cultural diversity.
[src:india/india-p01] No ruler of this period was able to create an empire and consistently control lands much beyond their core region.
[src:india/india-p01] During this time, pastoral peoples, whose land had been cleared to make way for the growing agricultural economy, were accommodated within caste society, as were new non-traditional ruling classes.
[src:india/india-p01] The caste system consequently began to show regional differences.
[src:india/india-p01] In the 6th and 7th centuries, the first devotional hymns were composed in Tamil.
[src:india/india-p01] They were imitated all over India and led to both the resurgence of Hinduism and the development of all modern languages of the subcontinent.
[src:india/india-p01] Indian royalty, big and small, and the temples they patronised drew citizens in significant numbers to the capital cities, which became economic hubs as well.
[src:india/india-p01] Temple towns of various sizes began to appear everywhere as India underwent another urbanisation.
[src:india/india-p01] By the 8th and 9th centuries, the effects were felt in Southeast Asia, as South Indian culture and political systems were exported to lands that became part of modern-day Myanmar, Thailand, Laos, Brunei, Cambodia, Vietnam, Philippines, Malaysia, and Indonesia.
[src:india/india-p01] Indian merchants, scholars, and sometimes armies were involved in this transmission; Southeast Asians took the initiative as well, with many sojourning in Indian seminaries and translating Buddhist and Hindu texts into their languages.
[src:india/india-p01] After the 10th century, Muslim Central Asian nomadic clans, using swift-horse cavalry and raising vast armies united by ethnicity, repeatedly overran South Asia's north-western plains, leading eventually to the establishment of the Islamic Delhi Sultanate in 1206.
[src:india/india-p01] The sultanate was to control much of North India and to make many forays into South India.
[src:india/india-p01] Although at first disruptive for the Indian elites, the sultanate largely left its vast non-Muslim subject population to its own laws and customs.
[src:india/india-p01] The sultanate's raiding and weakening of the regional kingdoms of South India paved the way for the indigenous Vijayanagara Empire.
[src:india/india-p01] Embracing a strong Shaivite tradition and building upon the military technology of the sultanate, the empire came to control a large portion of peninsular India, and was to influence South Indian society for long afterwards.
[src:india/india-p01] In the early 16th century, northern India, then under mainly Muslim rulers, fell again to the superior mobility and firepower of a new generation of Central Asian warriors.
[src:india/india-p01] The resulting Mughal Empire did not stamp out the local societies it came to rule.
[src:india/india-p01] Instead, it balanced and pacified them through new administrative practices and diverse and inclusive ruling elites, leading to more systematic, centralised, and uniform rule.
[src:india/india-p01] Eschewing tribal bonds and Islamic identity, especially under Akbar, the Mughals united their far-flung realms through loyalty—expressed through a Persianised culture—to an emperor who had near-divine status.
[src:india/india-p01] The Mughal state's economic policies, deriving most revenues from agriculture and mandating that taxes be paid in the well-regulated silver currency, caused peasants and artisans to enter larger markets.
[src:india/india-p01] The relative peace maintained by the empire during much of the 17th century was a factor in India's economic expansion, resulting in greater patronage of painting, literary forms, textiles, and architecture.
[src:india/india-p01] Newly coherent social groups in northern and western India, such as the Marathas, the Rajputs, and the Sikhs, gained military and governing ambitions during Mughal rule, which, through collaboration or adversity, gave them both recognition and military experience.
[src:india/india-p01] Expanding commerce during Mughal rule gave rise to new Indian commercial and political elites along the coasts of southern and eastern India.
[src:india/india-p01] The incremental fragmentation of imperial authority during the late 17th and 18th centuries facilitated a process of decentralisation, enabling provincial elites to assert localised autonomy and consolidate control over their own affairs.
[src:india/india-p01] By the early 18th century, with the lines between commercial enterprise and political sovereignty increasingly blurred, European chartered companies—notably the English East India Company—solidified their presence through fortified coastal outposts.
[src:india/india-p01] Its further access to the riches of Bengal and the subsequent increased strength and size of its army enabled it to annexe or subdue most of India by the 1820s.
[src:india/india-p01] India was no longer exporting manufactured goods as it long had, but instead supplying the British Empire with raw materials.
[src:india/india-p01] Many historians consider this to be the onset of India's colonial period.
[src:india/india-p01] By this time, with its economic power severely curtailed by the British parliament and having effectively been made an arm of British administration, the East India Company began more consciously to enter non-economic arenas, including education, social reform, and culture.
[src:india/india-p01] The appointment in 1848 of Lord Dalhousie as Governor General of the East India Company set the stage for changes essential to a modern state: the consolidation and demarcation of sovereignty, the surveillance of the population, and the education of citizens.
[src:india/india-p01] Technological changes—among them, railways, canals, and the telegraph—were introduced not long after their introduction in Europe.
[src:india/india-p01] Disaffection with the company also grew during this time and set off the Indian Rebellion of 1857.
[src:india/india-p01] Fed by diverse resentments and perceptions, including invasive British-style social reforms, harsh land taxes, and summary treatment of some wealthy landowners and princes, the rebellion rocked many regions of northern and central India and shook the foundations of Company rule.
[src:india/india-p01] After the rebellion was suppressed in 1858, the East India Company was disbanded, and the British government began to directly administer India.
[src:india/india-p01] Proclaiming a unitary state and a gradual but limited British-style parliamentary system, the new rulers also protected princes and landed gentry as a feudal safeguard against future unrest.
[src:india/india-p01] In the decades following, public life gradually emerged across India, eventually leading to the founding of the Indian National Congress in 1885.
[src:india/india-p01] The rush of technology and the commercialisation of agriculture in the second half of the 19th century was marked by economic setbacks, and many small farmers became dependent on the whims of faraway markets.
[src:india/india-p01] There was an increase in the number of large-scale famines, and, despite the risks of infrastructure development borne by Indian taxpayers, little industrial employment was generated for Indians.
[src:india/india-p01] However, commercial cropping, especially in the newly canalled Punjab, led to increased food production for internal consumption.
[src:india/india-p01] The railway network provided critical famine relief, notably reduced the cost of moving goods, and helped nascent Indian-owned industry.
[src:india/india-p01] After World War I, in which more than 1.3 million Indians served, the Gandhian era began.
[src:india/india-p01] It was marked by British reforms but also repressive legislation, by more strident Indian calls for self-rule, and by the beginnings of a nonviolent movement of non-co-operation led by Mahatma Gandhi.
[src:india/india-p01] During the 1930s, the British enacted slow legislative reform; the Indian National Congress won victories in the resulting elections.
[src:india/india-p01] The next decade was beset with crises: Indian participation in World War II, the Congress's final push for non-co-operation, and an upsurge of Muslim nationalism.
[src:india/india-p01] All were capped by the advent of independence in 1947, but tempered by the partition of India into two states: India and Pakistan.
[src:india/india-p01] India's constitution was adopted in 1950 and established a secular, democratic republic.
[src:india/india-p01] Economic liberalisation has created a large urban middle class and transformed India into a fast growing economy.
[src:india/india-p01] However, India has been hamstrung by persistent poverty, both rural and urban; religious- and caste-related violence; Maoist-inspired Naxalite insurgencies; and separatism in Jammu and Kashmir and in Northeast India.
[src:india/india-p01] India has unresolved territorial disputes with China and with Pakistan.
[src:india/india-p01] India accounts for the bulk of the Indian subcontinent, lying atop the Indian tectonic plate, and a part of the Indo-Australian Plate.
[src:india/india-p01] India's defining geologic processes began approximately 70 million years ago, when the Indian Plate, then part of the southern supercontinent Gondwana, began a north-eastward drift caused by seafloor spreading to its south-west, and later, south and south-east.
[src:india/india-p01] Simultaneously, the vast Tethyan oceanic crust, to its northeast, began to subduct under the Eurasian Plate.
[src:india/india-p01] The Indian continental crust, however, was obstructed and was sheared horizontally.
[src:india/india-p01] Its lower crust and mantle slid under, but the upper layer piled up in sheets (or nappes) ahead of the subduction zone.
[src:india/india-p01] This created the orogeny, or process of mountain building, of the Himalayas.
[src:india/india-p01] The middle and stiffer layer continued to push into Tibet, causing crustal thickening of the Tibetan Plateau.
[src:india/india-p01] Immediately south of the emerging Himalayas, plate movement created a vast crescent-shaped trough that rapidly filled with river-borne sediment and now constitutes the Indo-Gangetic Plain.
[src:india/india-p01] The original Indian plate makes its first appearance above the sediment in the ancient Aravalli range, which extends from the Delhi Ridge in a southwesterly direction.
[src:india/india-p01] To the west lies the Thar Desert, the eastern spread of which is checked by the Aravallis.
[src:india/india-p01] The remaining Indian Plate survives as peninsular India, the oldest and geologically most stable part of India.
[src:india/india-p01] It extends as far north as the Satpura and Vindhya ranges in central India.
[src:india/india-p01] These parallel chains run from the Arabian Sea coast in Gujarat in the west to the coal-rich Chota Nagpur Plateau in Jharkhand in the east.
[src:india/india-p01] To the south, the remaining peninsular landmass, the Deccan Plateau, is flanked on the west and east by coastal ranges known as the Western and Eastern Ghats; the plateau contains the country's oldest rock formations, some over one billion years old.
[src:india/india-p01] Constituted in such fashion, India lies to the north of the equator between 6° 44′ and 35° 30′ north latitude and 68° 7′ and 97° 25′ east longitude.
[src:india/india-p01] Major Himalayan-origin rivers that substantially flow through India include the Ganges and the Brahmaputra, both of which drain into the Bay of Bengal.
[src:india/india-p01] Important tributaries of the Ganges include the Yamuna and the Kosi.
[src:india/india-p01] The Kosi's extremely low gradient, caused by long-term silt deposition, leads to severe floods and course changes.
[src:india/india-p01] Major peninsular rivers, whose steeper gradients prevent their waters from flooding, include the Godavari, the Mahanadi, the Kaveri, and the Krishna, which also drain into the Bay of Bengal; and the Narmada and the Tapti, which drain into the Arabian Sea.
[src:india/india-p01] India's coastline measures 7,517 kilometres (4,700 mi) in length; of this distance, 5,423 kilometres (3,400 mi) belong to peninsular India and 2,094 kilometres (1,300 mi) to the Andaman, Nicobar, and Lakshadweep island chains.
[src:india/india-p01] According to the Indian naval hydrographic charts, the mainland coastline consists of the following: 43% sandy beaches; 11% rocky shores, including cliffs; and 46% mudflats or marshy shores.
[src:india/india-p01] Coastal features include the marshy Rann of Kutch of western India and the alluvial Sundarbans delta of eastern India; the latter is shared with Bangladesh.
[src:india/india-p01] India has two archipelagos: the Lakshadweep coral atolls off India's south-western coast; and the Andaman and Nicobar Islands, a volcanic chain in the Andaman Sea.
[src:india/india-p01] India has 28 states and 8 union territories.
[src:india/india-p01] The Indian climate is strongly influenced by the Himalayas and the Thar Desert, both of which drive the economically and culturally pivotal summer and winter monsoons.
[src:india/india-p01] The Himalayas prevent cold Central Asian katabatic winds from blowing in, keeping the bulk of the Indian subcontinent warmer than most locations at similar latitudes.
[src:india/india-p01] The Thar Desert plays a crucial role in attracting the moisture-laden south-west summer monsoon winds that, between June and October, provide the majority of India's rainfall.
[src:india/india-p01] Four major climatic groupings predominate in India: tropical wet, tropical dry, subtropical humid, and montane.
[src:india/india-p01] Temperatures in India have risen by 0.7 °C (1.3 °F) between 1901 and 2018.
[src:india/india-p01] Climate change in India is often thought to be the cause.
[src:india/india-p01] The retreat of Himalayan glaciers has adversely affected the flow rate of the major Himalayan rivers, including the Ganges and the Brahmaputra.
[src:india/india-p01] According to some current projections, the number and severity of droughts in India will have markedly increased by the end of the present century.
[src:india/india-p01] India is a megadiverse country, a term employed for 17 countries that host high biological diversity and contain many species indigenous, or endemic, to them.
[src:india/india-p01] India is the habitat for 8.6% of all mammals, 13.7% of bird species, 7.9% of reptile species, 6% of amphibian species, 12.2% of fish species, and 6.0% of all flowering plant species.
[src:india/india-p01] Fully a third of Indian plant species are endemic.
[src:india/india-p01] India also overlaps four of the world's 34 biodiversity hotspots, or regions that display significant habitat loss in the presence of high endemism.
[src:india/india-p01] India's most dense forests, such as the tropical moist forest of the Andaman Islands, the Western Ghats, and Northeast India, occupy approximately 3% of its land area.
[src:india/india-p01] *Moderately dense forest*, whose canopy density is between 40% and 70%, occupies 9.39% of India's land area.
[src:india/india-p01] It predominates in the temperate coniferous forest of the Himalayas, the moist deciduous *sal* forest of eastern India, and the dry deciduous teak forest of central and southern India.
[src:india/india-p01] India has two natural zones of thorn forest, one in the Deccan Plateau, immediately east of the Western Ghats, and the other in the western part of the Indo-Gangetic plain, now turned into rich agricultural land by irrigation, its features no longer visible.
[src:india/india-p01] Many Indian species have descended from those of Gondwana, the southern supercontinent from which India separated more than 100 million years ago.
[src:india/india-p01] India's subsequent collision with Eurasia set off a mass exchange of species.
[src:india/india-p01] However, volcanism and climatic changes later caused the extinction of many endemic Indian forms.
[src:india/india-p01] Still later, mammals entered India from Asia through two zoogeographic passes flanking the Himalayas.
[src:india/india-p01] This lowered endemism among India's mammals, which stands at 12.6%, contrasting with 45.8% among reptiles and 55.8% among amphibians.
[src:india/india-p01] Among endemics are the vulnerable hooded leaf monkey and the threatened Beddome's toad of the Western Ghats.
[src:india/india-p01] India contains 172 IUCN-designated threatened animal species, or 2.9% of endangered forms.
[src:india/india-p01] These include the endangered Bengal tiger and the Ganges river dolphin.
[src:india/india-p01] Critically endangered species include the gharial, a crocodilian; the great Indian bustard; and the Indian white-rumped vulture, which has become nearly extinct by having ingested the carrion of diclofenac-treated cattle.
[src:india/india-p01] The pervasive and ecologically devastating human encroachment of recent decades has critically endangered Indian wildlife.
[src:india/india-p01] In response, the system of national parks and protected areas, first established in 1935, was expanded substantially.
[src:india/india-p01] In 1972, India enacted the Wildlife Protection Act and Project Tiger to safeguard crucial wilderness; the Forest Conservation Act was enacted in 1980 and amendments added in 1988.
[src:india/india-p01] India hosts more than five hundred wildlife sanctuaries and eighteen biosphere reserves, four of which are part of the World Network of Biosphere Reserves; its eighty-nine wetlands are registered under the Ramsar Convention.
[src:india/india-p01] India is a parliamentary republic with a multi-party system.
[src:india/india-p01] There are six recognised national parties in the country, including the Indian National Congress (generally, "the Congress") and the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP); there are over 50 regional parties.
[src:india/india-p01] The Congress is considered the ideological centre in Indian political culture; the BJP is right-wing to far-right.
[src:india/india-p01] After India's independence on August 15, 1947, Jawaharlal Nehru became prime minister of the Dominion of India, an office he held until January 26, 1950, when India became a republic; Nehru remained the caretaker prime minister until the following year.
[src:india/india-p01] In the general elections in 1951, 1957, and 1962, the Congress, led by Nehru, won by comfortable margins.
[src:india/india-p01] After Nehru died in office in May 1964, Lal Bahadur Shastri was unanimously chosen by the Congress to be parliamentary leader, and thus prime minister.
[src:india/india-p01] After the India–Pakistan war of 1965, Shastri died in January 1966, soon after signing the Tashkent Peace Declaration.
[src:india/india-p01] The Congress chose Indira Gandhi to be prime minister.
[src:india/india-p01] She led the party to election victories in 1967 and 1971, the latter a landslide after Pakistan's defeat in the Bangladesh Liberation War.
[src:india/india-p01] In 1975, Indira Gandhi declared a state of emergency, suspending many civil liberties.
[src:india/india-p01] Following public discontent with the Emergency, the Congress was voted out of power in 1977; Janata Party, which had opposed the Emergency, was voted in.
[src:india/india-p01] Its government lasted two years; Morarji Desai and Charan Singh served as prime ministers.
[src:india/india-p01] After a military operation against Sikh militants occupying the Golden Temple in Amritsar, Indira Gandhi was assassinated by a Sikh bodyguard on October 31, 1984.
[src:india/india-p01] She was succeeded as prime minister by Rajiv Gandhi, who led Congress to a comfortable victory in the elections at the end of the year.
[src:india/india-p01] In 1989, a National Front coalition, led by the Janata Dal, in alliance with the Left Front, won the general elections.
[src:india/india-p01] The subsequent government lasted just under two years; V.
[src:india/india-p01] Singh and Chandra Shekhar served as prime ministers.
[src:india/india-p01] In 1991, soon after the first round of polling in the general election, Congress leader Rajiv Gandhi was assassinated by a member of a Sri Lankan Tamil separatist organisation who was seeking to avenge Indian intervention in the Sri Lankan civil war.
[src:india/india-p01] After the elections, Congress emerged as the largest single party; a new Congress leader, P.
[src:india/india-p01] Narasimha Rao, formed a minority government which served a full five-year term.
[src:india/india-p01] In 1996, the BJP briefly formed a government after winning the general election.
[src:india/india-p01] United Front coalition governments followed, which relied on external political support, H.
[src:india/india-p01] After the 1998 Indian general election, Atal Bihari Vajpayee of the BJP became prime minister; his government was short-lived due to the lack of a continued mandate.
[src:india/india-p01] The BJP, now a part of the National Democratic Alliance (NDA), formed a coalition government led by Vajpayee, who became the first non-Congress prime minister to complete a five-year term.
[src:india/india-p01] In the 2004 general election, the NDA was defeated.
[src:india/india-p01] Congress emerged as the largest single party and formed a coalition, the United Progressive Alliance (UPA).
[src:india/india-p01] Manmohan Singh, a Sikh, who was proposed by Congress President Sonia Gandhi to be parliamentary leader, served as prime minister of the UPA government, but with some external support.
[src:india/india-p01] The UPA returned to power in the 2009 general election with increased numbers, no longer dependent on external support.
[src:india/india-p01] Singh became the first prime minister to be re-elected after Jawaharlal Nehru in 1962.
[src:india/india-p01] In the 2014 general election, the BJP under Narendra Modi became the first political party since 1984 to win an absolute majority.
[src:india/india-p01] The party won a larger majority in the 2019 general election.
[src:india/india-p01] After losing its majority in the 2024 general election, the BJP formed a coalition government with its NDA partners.
[src:india/india-p01] Modi is the longest-serving non-Congress prime minister.
[src:india/india-p01] Democratic backsliding was found by the 2026 V-Dem Democracy Report.
[src:india/india-p01] The Constitution of India was drafted by the Constituent Assembly of India with uncommon speed and absence of irregularities between 1946 and 1949.
[src:india/india-p01] The Government of India Act 1935 was used as a model and framework.
[src:india/india-p01] Long passages from the Act were included.
[src:india/india-p01] The constitution describes a federal state with a parliamentary system of democracy.
[src:india/india-p01] The federal structure was conspicuous for the strength of the central government, which exclusively exercised control of defence, foreign affairs, railways, ports, and currency.
[src:india/india-p01] The President, the constitutional head of state, has reserve powers for taking over the administration of a state.
[src:india/india-p01] The central legislature has two houses: the *Lok Sabha*, whose delegates are directly elected by the people in general elections every five years, and the *Rajya Sabha*, whose members are nominated by the elected representatives in the states.
[src:india/india-p01] There are also features not to be found in the Act of 1935.
[src:india/india-p01] The definition of fundamental rights is based on the Constitution of the United States, and the constitutional directives, or goals of endeavor, are based on the Constitution of Ireland.
[src:india/india-p01] An Indian institution recommended by the constitution is the *panchayat* or village committees.
[src:india/india-p01] Untouchability is illegal (Article 17) and caste distinctions are derecognized (Articles 15(2) and 16(2)).
[src:india/india-p01] The promulgation of the Indian constitution transformed India into a republic within the Commonwealth.
[src:india/india-p01] The prime minister of India is the head of government and exercises most executive power.
[src:india/india-p01] Appointed by the president, the prime minister is supported by the party or political alliance with a majority of seats in the lower house of parliament.
[src:india/india-p01] The executive of the Indian government consists of the president, the vice-president, and the Union Council of Ministers—with the cabinet being its executive committee—headed by the prime minister.
[src:india/india-p01] Any minister holding a portfolio must be a member of one of the houses of parliament.
[src:india/india-p01] In the Indian parliamentary system, the executive is subordinate to the legislature; the prime minister and their council are directly responsible to the lower house of the parliament.
[src:india/india-p01] Civil servants act as permanent executives and all decisions of the executive are implemented by them.
[src:india/india-p01] India has a three-tier unitary independent judiciary comprising the supreme court, headed by the Chief Justice of India, 25 high courts, and a large number of trial courts.
[src:india/india-p01] The supreme court has original jurisdiction over cases involving fundamental rights and over disputes between states and the centre and has appellate jurisdiction over the high courts.
[src:india/india-p01] It has the power to both strike down union or state laws which contravene the constitution and invalidate any government action it deems unconstitutional.
[src:india/india-p01] India is a federal union comprising 28 states and 8 union territories.
[src:india/india-p01] All states, as well as the union territories of Jammu and Kashmir, Puducherry and the National Capital Territory of Delhi, have elected legislatures and governments following the Westminster system.
[src:india/india-p01] The remaining five union territories are directly ruled by the central government through appointed administrators.
[src:india/india-p01] In 1956, under the States Reorganisation Act, states were reorganised on a linguistic basis.
[src:india/india-p01] There are over a quarter of a million local government bodies at city, town, district, block and village levels.
[src:india/india-p01] India remained a member of the Commonwealth of Nations after becoming a republic in 1950.
[src:india/india-p01] It strongly supported decolonisation in Africa and Asia in the 1950s, and played a leading role in the Non-Aligned Movement.
[src:india/india-p01] After cordial relations with China during the greater part of the 1950s, India and China went to war in 1962; India was widely thought to have been decisively defeated.
[src:india/india-p01] By 1967, however, India was able to fend off Chinese excursions into Sikkim.
[src:india/india-p01] India has had uneasy relations with its western neighbour, Pakistan.
[src:india/india-p01] Three wars were fought over the disputed territory of Kashmir.
[src:india/india-p01] After the 1965 war, India began to pursue close military and economic ties with the Soviet Union.
[src:india/india-p01] By the late 1960s, the Soviet Union was India's largest arms supplier.
[src:india/india-p01] China's nuclear test of 596 and threats to intervene in support of Pakistan in the 1965 war caused India to produce nuclear weapons.
[src:india/india-p01] India conducted its first nuclear weapons test in 1974 and carried out additional underground testing in 1998.
[src:india/india-p01] India has signed neither the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty nor the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, considering both to be flawed and discriminatory.
[src:india/india-p01] India maintains a "no first use" nuclear policy and is developing a nuclear triad capability as a part of its "Minimum Credible Deterrence" doctrine.
[src:india/india-p01] Since the end of the Cold War, India has increased its economic, strategic, and military cooperation with the United States and the European Union.
[src:india/india-p01] In 2008, a civilian nuclear agreement was signed between India and the United States.
[src:india/india-p02] The Indian economy has been among the ten largest economies in the world since 2010.
[src:india/india-p02] As of 2026, Indian gross domestic output (GDP) have placed the nation as the 6th largest economy in the world.
[src:india/india-p02] Measured by purchasing power parity (PPP), India is the third-largest economy.
[src:india/india-p02] It is one of the world's fastest-growing economies with an average annual growth rate exceeding 5% from 1990 to 2010.
[src:india/india-p02] Demographics strain its economy, with the nation historically maintaining low GDP per capita both regionally and as measured by globally.
[src:india/india-p02] The vast majority of Indians fall into the global low-income group based on average daily income.
[src:india/india-p02] Until 1991, all Indian governments followed protectionist policies that were influenced by socialist economics.
[src:india/india-p02] Widespread state intervention and regulation largely walled the economy off from the outside world.
[src:india/india-p02] An acute balance of payments crisis in 1991 forced the nation to liberalise its economy; since then, it has moved increasingly towards a free-market system by emphasising both foreign trade and direct investment inflows.
[src:india/india-p02] India has been a member of World Trade Organization since 1 January 1995.
[src:india/india-p02] The 522-million-worker Indian labour force is the world's second largest, as of 2017.
[src:india/india-p02] The service sector makes up 55.6% of GDP, the industrial sector 26.3% and the agricultural sector 18.1%.
[src:india/india-p02] India's foreign exchange remittances of US$100 billion in 2022, the highest in the world, were contributed to its economy by 32 million Indians working in foreign countries.
[src:india/india-p02] In 2006, the share of external trade in India's GDP stood at 24%, up from 6% in 1985.
[src:india/india-p02] In 2008, India's share of world trade was 1.6%; in 2021, it was the world's ninth-largest importer and the sixteenth-largest exporter.
[src:india/india-p02] Between 2001 and 2011, the contribution of petrochemical and engineering goods to total exports grew from 14% to 42%.
[src:india/india-p02] India was the world's second-largest textile exporter after China in the 2013 calendar year.
[src:india/india-p02] Averaging an economic growth rate of 7.5% for several years before 2007, India has more than doubled its hourly wage rates during the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:india/india-p02] Some 431 million Indians have left poverty since 1985; India's middle classes are projected to number around 580 million by 2030.
[src:india/india-p02] In 2024, India's consumer market was the world's third largest.
[src:india/india-p02] India's nominal GDP per capita increased steadily from US$308 in 1991, when economic liberalisation began, to US$1,380 in 2010, to an estimated US$2,731 in 2024.
[src:india/india-p02] It is expected to grow to US$3,264 by 2026.
[src:india/india-p02] The Indian automotive industry, the world's second-fastest growing, increased domestic sales by 26% during 2009–2010, and exports by 36% during 2008–2009.
[src:india/india-p02] In 2022, India became the world's third-largest vehicle market after China and the United States, surpassing Japan.
[src:india/india-p02] At the end of 2011, the Indian IT industry employed 2.8 million professionals, generated revenues close to US$100 billion equalling 7.5% of Indian GDP, and contributed 26% of India's merchandise exports.
[src:india/india-p02] India's local pharmaceutical market is estimated up to US$42 billion.
[src:india/india-p02] India is among the top 12 biotech destinations in the world.
[src:india/india-p02] The Indian biotech industry grew by 15.1% in 2012–2013, increasing its revenues from ₹204.4 billion (Indian rupees) to ₹235.24 billion (US$3.94 billion at June 2013 exchange rates).
[src:india/india-p02] India's capacity to generate electrical power is 300 gigawatts, of which 42 gigawatts is renewable.
[src:india/india-p02] The country's usage of coal is a major cause of India's greenhouse gas emissions, but its renewable energy is growing.
[src:india/india-p02] India emits about 7% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:india/india-p02] This equates to about 2.5 tons of carbon dioxide per person per year, which is half the world average.
[src:india/india-p02] Increasing access to electricity and clean cooking with liquefied petroleum gas have been priorities for energy in India.
[src:india/india-p02] With an estimated 1,428,627,663 residents in 2023, India is the world's most populous country.
[src:india/india-p02] 1,210,193,422 residents were reported in the 2011 provisional census report.
[src:india/india-p02] The first post-colonial census, conducted in 1951, counted 361 million people.
[src:india/india-p02] The life expectancy at birth has increased from 49.7 years in 1970–1975 to 72.0 years in 2023.
[src:india/india-p02] The under-five mortality rate for the country was 113 per 1,000 live births in 1994 whereas in 2018 it reduced to 41.1 per 1,000 live births.
[src:india/india-p02] The human sex ratio, according to the 2011 census, is 940 females per 1,000 males.
[src:india/india-p02] Female infanticide in India, and lately female foeticide, have created lop-sided gender ratios; the number of missing women in the country quadrupled from 15 million to 63 million during the period 1964–2014, faster than the population growth during the same period.
[src:india/india-p02] According to an Indian government study, an additional 21 million girls are unwanted and do not receive adequate care.
[src:india/india-p02] Despite a government ban on sex-selective foeticide, the practice has far from stopped.
[src:india/india-p02] Migration from rural to urban areas has been an important dynamic in India's recent history.
[src:india/india-p02] The number of people living in urban areas grew by 31.2% between 1991 and 2001.
[src:india/india-p02] The level of urbanisation increased further from 27.81% in the 2001 census to 31.16% in the 2011 census.
[src:india/india-p02] The slowing down of the overall population growth rate was due to the sharp decline in the growth rate in rural areas since 1991.
[src:india/india-p02] In the 2011 census, there were 53 million-plus urban agglomerations in India.
[src:india/india-p02] Among them Mumbai, Delhi, Kolkata, Chennai, Bengaluru, Hyderabad and Ahmedabad, in decreasing order by population.
[src:india/india-p02] Languages of India belong to several language families.
[src:india/india-p02] There are also small numbers of speakers of Tai–Kadai, Andamanese, and minor language families and isolates.
[src:india/india-p02] The official language of India's federal government was chosen by the Constituent Assembly of India in September 1949 after three years of debate between two opposing camps.
[src:india/india-p02] Hindi language protagonists wanted Hindi in the Devanagari script to be the sole "national language" of India whereas delegates from South India preferred English to have a place in the Constitution.
[src:india/india-p02] The compromise resolution became articles 343–351 of India's constitution, which came into effect on 26 January 1950.
[src:india/india-p02] In 1965, after bitter opposition from South India to Hindi becoming the sole official language, a compromise was reached to where English would continue to be an "associate official language" indefinitely.
[src:india/india-p02] The Eighth Schedule of India's Constitution also recognises 22 languages, including Hindi but not English, which the government is obligated to develop.
[src:india/india-p02] These are sometimes called "scheduled languages".
[src:india/india-p02] This list includes major regional languages, but also others—such as Sanskrit, which no longer has first language speakers in India, and Urdu, which is not region-specific—because of their value to India's cultural heritage.
[src:india/india-p02] In 1950, there were 14 scheduled languages: Assamese, Bengali, Gujarati, Hindi, Kannada, Kashmiri, Malayalam, Marathi, Oriya, Punjabi, Sanskrit, Tamil, Telugu and Urdu.
[src:india/india-p02] In the following decades constitutional amendments added others: Sindhi (1967), Nepali, Manipuri, and Konkani (1992), Maithili, Dogri, Santali and Bodo (2004).
[src:india/india-p02] Religion in India is characterised by a diversity of beliefs and practices.
[src:india/india-p02] Throughout India's history, religion has been an important part of its culture.
[src:india/india-p02] The Indian subcontinent is the birthplace of four major world religions: Buddhism, Hinduism, Jainism, and Sikhism.
[src:india/india-p02] India has the largest population of Hindus, Sikhs, and Jains, the third-largest population of Muslims (after Indonesia and Pakistan) and the ninth largest of Buddhists.
[src:india/india-p02] India also has the largest population of people adhering to both Zoroastrianism (Parsis and Iranis) and the Bahá'í Faith.
[src:india/india-p02] Several tribal religions are also present in India, such as Donyi-Polo, Sanamahism, Sarnaism, and Niamtre.
[src:india/india-p02] The rural-urban literacy gap, which was 21.2 percentage points in 2001, dropped to 16.1 percentage points in 2011.
[src:india/india-p02] The improvement in the rural literacy rate is twice that of urban areas.
[src:india/india-p02] In 2011 Kerala had the highest literary rate, with 93.91% literacy, and Bihar the lowest, with 63.82%.
[src:india/india-p02] In 1981 the respective literacy rates for total population, men and women were 41%, 53% and 29%.
[src:india/india-p02] According to Latika Chaudhary, in 1911 there were under three primary schools for every ten villages.
[src:india/india-p02] Statistically, more caste and religious diversity reduced private spending.
[src:india/india-p02] Primary schools taught literacy, so local diversity limited its growth.
[src:india/india-p02] The education system of India is the world's second-largest.
[src:india/india-p02] India has over 900 universities, 40,000 colleges and 1.5 million schools.
[src:india/india-p02] In India's higher education system, a significant number of seats are reserved under affirmative action policies for the historically disadvantaged.
[src:india/india-p02] In recent decades India's improved education system is often cited as one of the main contributors to its economic development.
[src:india/india-p02] India bears a disproportionately large burden of the world's tuberculosis rates, with World Health Organization (WHO) statistics for 2022 estimating 2.8 million new infections annually, accounting for 26% of the global total.
[src:india/india-p02] It is estimated that approximately 40% of the population of India carry tuberculosis infection.
[src:india/india-p02] In 2018 chronic obstructive pulmonary disease was the leading cause of death after heart disease.
[src:india/india-p02] The 10 most polluted cities in the world are all in India with more than 140 million people breathing air 10 times or more over the WHO safe limit.
[src:india/india-p02] As of 2026, air quality reports show that not a single Indian city meets the WHO's safety guidelines.
[src:india/india-p02] In cities like Delhi and Mumbai, breathing the air is equivalent to smoking 30 cigarettes a day.
[src:india/india-p02] In 2017, air pollution killed 1.24 million Indians.
[src:india/india-p02] Although sometimes applied to other cultures and religions, caste is a uniquely Indian, and Hindu, social institution.
[src:india/india-p02] All Hindus fall broadly into four castes, or *varnas*: Brahmin, or priests, at the top; below them Kshatriya, or warriors; further below, Vaishya, or merchants and farmers; and at the bottom, Shudra, or the service class.
[src:india/india-p02] Outside the caste system, and therefore of traditional Hinduism, lie people formerly called "outcastes" or "untouchables," and now scheduled caste (a term used in India's constitution) or Dalit, a later self-description of pride, meaning "broken" or "downtrodden".
[src:india/india-p02] Each caste is further divided into sub-castes, or jatis, many of which are tied to occupations.
[src:india/india-p02] The custom of endogamy, or marrying within one's subcaste, however, makes caste a hereditary label, not of one occupational choice, and has caused the caste system, therefore, to become entrenched.
[src:india/india-p02] The Constituent Assembly of India abolished untouchability in 1947, the Republic of India did more formally in 1950, and India has since enacted other anti-discriminatory laws and social welfare initiatives related to caste.
[src:india/india-p02] Still, caste-based inequality, discrimination, segregation, and violence persist.
[src:india/india-p02] Multi-generational patrilineal joint families have been the norm in India, though nuclear families are becoming common in urban areas.
[src:india/india-p02] A very large majority of Indians have their marriages arranged by their parents or family elders.
[src:india/india-p02] Marriage is thought to be for life; and the divorce rate is extremely low; less than one in a thousand marriages end in divorce.
[src:india/india-p02] Many women marry before reaching 18, which is their legal marriageable age; child marriages are not uncommon, especially in rural areas.
[src:india/india-p02] India has a very ancient tradition of art, which has exchanged many influences with the rest of Eurasia, especially in the first millennium.
[src:india/india-p02] During this period Buddhist art spread with Indian religions to Central, East and Southeast Asia, the last also greatly influenced by Hindu art.
[src:india/india-p02] Thousands of seals from the Indus Valley civilisation of the third millennium BCE have been found, usually carved with animals, but also some with human figures.
[src:india/india-p02] The Pashupati seal, excavated in Mohenjo-daro, Pakistan, in 1928–29, is the best known.
[src:india/india-p02] Virtually no art survives from a long period following the Indus Valley Civilisation.
[src:india/india-p02] Almost all surviving ancient Indian art thereafter is in various forms of religious sculpture in durable materials, or coins.
[src:india/india-p02] There was probably originally far more in wood, which is lost.
[src:india/india-p02] In north India Mauryan art is the first imperial movement.
[src:india/india-p02] Over the following centuries a distinctly Indian style of sculpting the human figure developed, with less interest in articulating precise anatomy than ancient Greek sculpture but showing smoothly flowing forms expressing *prana* ("breath" or life-force).
[src:india/india-p02] This is often complicated by the need to give figures multiple arms or heads, or represent different genders on the left and right of figures, as with the Ardhanarishvara form of Shiva and Parvati.
[src:india/india-p02] Most of the earliest large sculpture is Buddhist, either excavated from Buddhist stupas such as Sanchi, Sarnath and Amaravati, or is rock cut reliefs at sites such as Ajanta, Karla and Ellora.
[src:india/india-p02] Hindu and Jain sites appear rather later.
[src:india/india-p02] In spite of this complex mixture of religious traditions, generally, the prevailing artistic style at any time and place has been shared by the major religious groups, and sculptors probably usually served all communities.
[src:india/india-p02] 500 CE, is often regarded as a classical period whose influence lingered for many centuries after; it saw a new dominance of Hindu sculpture, as at the Elephanta Caves.
[src:india/india-p02] Across the north, this became rather stiff and formulaic after c.
[src:india/india-p02] 800 CE, though rich with finely carved detail in the surrounds of statues.
[src:india/india-p02] But in the South, under the Pallava and Chola dynasties, sculpture in both stone and bronze had a sustained period of great achievement; the large bronzes with Shiva as Nataraja have become an iconic symbol of India.
[src:india/india-p02] Ancient paintings have only survived at a few sites, of which the crowded scenes of court life in the Ajanta Caves are some of the most important.
[src:india/india-p02] Painted manuscripts of religious texts survive from Eastern India from 10th century onwards, most of the earliest being Buddhist and later Jain.
[src:india/india-p02] These significantly influenced later artistic styles.
[src:india/india-p02] The Persian-derived Deccan painting, starting just before the Mughal miniature, between them give the first large body of secular painting, with an emphasis on portraits, and the recording of princely pleasures and wars.
[src:india/india-p02] The style spread to Hindu courts, especially among the Rajputs, and developed a variety of styles, with the smaller courts often the most innovative, with figures such as Nihâl Chand and Nainsukh.
[src:india/india-p02] As a market developed among European residents, it was supplied by Company painting by Indian artists with considerable Western influence.
[src:india/india-p02] In the 19th century, cheap Kalighat paintings of gods and everyday life, done on paper, were urban folk art from Calcutta, which later saw the Bengal School of Art, reflecting the art colleges founded by the British, the first movement in modern Indian painting.
[src:india/india-p02] Significant mathematics began in India in the first millennium BCE.
[src:india/india-p02] The *Śulba Sūtras* (literally, "Aphorisms of the Chords" in Vedic Sanskrit) (c.
[src:india/india-p02] 700–400 BCE) contain the earliest extant verbal expression of the Pythagorean theorem (although very likely it had been known to the Old Babylonians.) All mathematical works were orally transmitted until approximately 500 BCE; thereafter, they were transmitted both orally and in manuscript form.
[src:india/india-p02] The oldest extant mathematical document produced on the Indian subcontinent is the birch bark Bakhshali manuscript from the 7th century CE.
[src:india/india-p02] In the classical period of Indian mathematics (400 CE to 1200 CE), important contributions were made by Aryabhata, Brahmagupta, Bhaskara II, Varāhamihira, and Madhava.
[src:india/india-p02] The decimal number system in use today was first recorded in Indian mathematics.
[src:india/india-p02] Indian mathematicians made early contributions to the study of the concept of zero as a number, negative numbers, arithmetic, and algebra.
[src:india/india-p02] Trigonometry was further advanced in India, and the modern definitions of sine and cosine were developed there.
[src:india/india-p02] These mathematical concepts were transmitted to the Middle East, China, and Europe.
[src:india/india-p02] A later landmark in Indian mathematics was the development of the series expansions for trigonometric functions (sine, cosine, and arc tangent) by mathematicians of the Kerala school in the 15th century CE.
[src:india/india-p02] Their work, completed two centuries before the invention of calculus in Europe, provided the first example of a power series.
[src:india/india-p02] In the modern era Srinivasa Ramanujan made fundamental contributions to number theory.
[src:india/india-p02] India contains a wide array of musical practices, including many different folk musics from different regions.
[src:india/india-p02] Indian classical music has Vedic origins, and split in the 13th century into the two main traditions of Hindustani and Carnatic music.
[src:india/india-p02] Indian music has influenced western genres, including rock and jazz musicians during the 1960s counterculture.
[src:india/india-p02] Indian film music is music written for Indian cinema, generally composed by music directors and sung by playback singers.
[src:india/india-p02] Modern Indian pop takes influences from classical, folk, and western pop music.
[src:india/india-p02] Dance in India has drawn heavily from Indian classical dance traditions.
[src:india/india-p02] Many of these in turn arose in temples or other religious contexts.
[src:india/india-p02] Their sponsorship and promotion, however, has continued in secular, modern India.
[src:india/india-p02] India also has local and modern dance traditions.
[src:india/india-p02] Whether a dance is classical is determined by the Sangeet Natak Academi, the Indian government's organisation for performing arts.
[src:india/india-p02] Although more dances could perhaps meet the criteria for classical, the Akademi has chosen eight.
[src:india/india-p02] The best-known classical dance is Bharatnatyam, which began in the temple dances of Tamil devadasis.
[src:india/india-p02] Identified with "prostitutes and courtesans", their dancing was formally banned in 1947.
[src:india/india-p02] Concurrently, the dance was rehabilitated as a "pure" art form, with Rukmini Devi Arundale as a prominent figure.
[src:india/india-p02] A devdasi who went on to attain national and international prominence was Thanjavur Balasaraswati.
[src:india/india-p02] Some sources consider the dance-dramas Chhau of Jharkhand, West Bengal, and Odisha and Yakshagana of Karnataka to also belong to the classical tradition.
[src:india/india-p02] Local dance traditions vary widely across India.
[src:india/india-p02] Among 20th-century directions is the modern dance of Uday Shankar in which classical styles were employed but not adhered to rigidly.
[src:india/india-p02] Examples are dance-dramas based on the ancient Indian animal fables, *Panchatantra*, and Nehru's mid-century meditation on Indian history, *The Discovery of India*.
[src:india/india-p02] Dance has been an essential aspect of Indian films from the first talkies of the 1930s.
[src:india/india-p02] The individual and group dances of Bollywood, for example, show a broad range of influences, including classical, local, and Western popular dance.
[src:india/india-p02] Towards the end of the 20th century, innovations in British South Asian music and dance, such as Post-Bhangra, fed back into dance in India.
[src:india/india-p02] From ancient times until the advent of the modern, the most widely worn traditional dress in India was draped.
[src:india/india-p02] For women it took the form of a sari, a single piece of cloth many yards long.
[src:india/india-p02] The sari was traditionally wrapped around the lower body and the shoulder.
[src:india/india-p02] In its modern form, it is combined with an underskirt, or Indian petticoat, and tucked in along the waist band for more secure fastening.
[src:india/india-p02] It is also commonly worn with an Indian blouse, or choli, which serves as the primary upper-body garment, the sari's end—passing over the shoulder—covering the midriff and obscuring the upper body's contours.
[src:india/india-p02] For men, a similar but shorter length of cloth, the dhoti, has served as a lower-body garment.
[src:india/india-p02] The use of stitched clothes became widespread after Muslim rule was established by the Delhi sultanate (c.
[src:india/india-p02] 1300 CE) and continued by the Mughal Empire (c.
[src:india/india-p02] Among the garments introduced during this time and still commonly worn are: the shalwars and pyjamas, both styles of trousers, and the tunics kurta and kameez.
[src:india/india-p02] Shalwars are atypically wide at the waist but narrow to a cuffed bottom.
[src:india/india-p02] They are held up by a drawstring, which causes them to become pleated around the waist.
[src:india/india-p02] When the pants are cut quite narrow, on the bias, they are called churidars.
[src:india/india-p02] Its side seams left open below the waistline.
[src:india/india-p02] The kurta is traditionally collarless and made of cotton or silk; it is worn plain or with embroidered decoration, such as chikankari; and typically falls to either just above or just below the wearer's knees.
[src:india/india-p02] In the last 50 years, fashions have changed a great deal in India.
[src:india/india-p02] Increasingly, in urban northern India, the sari is no longer the apparel of everyday wear, though they remain popular on formal occasions.
[src:india/india-p02] The traditional shalwar kameez is rarely worn by younger urban women, who favour churidars or jeans.
[src:india/india-p02] In office settings, ubiquitous air conditioning allows men to wear sports jackets year-round.
[src:india/india-p02] For weddings and formal occasions, men in the middle and upper classes often wear bandhgala, or short Nehru jackets, with pants, with the groom and his groomsmen sporting sherwanis and churidars.
[src:india/india-p02] The foundation of a typical Indian meal is a cereal cooked plainly and complemented with savoury dishes.
[src:india/india-p02] The cooked cereal could be steamed rice; chapati, a thin unleavened bread; idli, a steamed breakfast cake; or dosa, a griddled pancake.
[src:india/india-p02] The savoury dishes might include lentils, pulses, vegetables, meat, poultry and fish commonly spiced with ginger and garlic, but also coriander, cumin, turmeric, cinnamon, cardamom and others.
[src:india/india-p02] In some instances, the ingredients may be mixed during the cooking process.
[src:india/india-p02] India has distinctive vegetarian cuisines, each a feature of the geographical and cultural histories of its adherents.
[src:india/india-p02] About 20% to 39% of India's population consists of vegetarians.
[src:india/india-p02] Although meat is eaten widely, the proportional consumption of meat is low.
[src:india/india-p02] The most significant import of cooking techniques into India during the last millennium occurred during the Mughal Empire, spreading into northern India from regions to its northwest, along with dishes such as pilaf.
[src:india/india-p02] Onions, garlic, almonds, and spices were added to the simple yogurt marinade of Persia.
[src:india/india-p02] Rice was partially cooked and layered alternately with sauteed meat, the pot sealed tightly, and slow cooked according to another Persian cooking technique, to produce biryani, a feature of festive dining in many parts of India.
[src:india/india-p02] The diversity of Indian food served worldwide has been partially concealed by the dominance of Punjabi cuisine.
[src:india/india-p02] Several traditional indigenous sports such as *kabaddi*, *kho kho*, *pehlwani* and *gilli-danda*, and also martial arts, such as *Kalarippayattu* and *marma adi* remain popular.
[src:india/india-p02] Chess is commonly held to have originated in India as *chaturaṅga*; There has been a rise in the number of Indian grandmasters.
[src:india/india-p02] Viswanathan Anand became the undisputed Chess World Champion in 2007 and held the status until 2013.
[src:india/india-p02] Parcheesi is derived from *Pachisi* another traditional Indian pastime, which in early modern times was played on a giant marble court by Mughal emperor Akbar.
[src:india/india-p02] Cricket is the most popular sport in India.
[src:india/india-p02] India is one of the more successful cricket teams, having won two Cricket World Cups, three T20 World Cups, and three Champions Trophies.
[src:india/india-p02] India has won a record eight field hockey gold medals in the summer Olympics.
